@Praveen-Rai commented on [Sun Aug 26 2018](https://github.com/dotnet/core/issues/1895)

I was using .Net Core 2.1.1 untill now, and recently updated the SDK to 2.1.401 (.Net Core Runtime 2.1.3). When i create a new project the version of Microsoft.AspNetCore.App and Microsoft.NETCore.App under Dependencies > SDK is still 2.1.1. Looking at the properties of Dependencies > NuGet, the package is being referenced from "C:\Program Files\dotnet\sdk\NuGetFallbackFolder\microsoft.aspnetcore.app\2.1.1"

I tried installing Package 2.1.3 using NuGet package manager, and it downloaded all dependencies (v2.1.3) from NuGet despite that i have 2.1.3 already installed on my machine.

I've tried specifying the version in the .csproj file, but again it downloads from the NuGet.

I am using VS 15.7.4 on Win 10 x64. And i have following .Net Core SDKs installed on my machine : 
1.1.0 , 2.0.0 , 2.1.201 , 2.1.301 , 2.1.302 , 2.1.401.

---

@uffebjorklund commented on [Mon Aug 27 2018](https://github.com/dotnet/core/issues/1895#issuecomment-416140058)

We control sdk-version by having a `global.json` in the root of our solution.
```
{
    "sdk": {
        "version": "2.1.401"
    }
}
```
We are on Linux and Mac (vscode), but I guess this should work when you are using Visual Studio as well.

